content.content: Orthopedic Surgery Consultation Note
**Patient:** Artie Jointston, DOB: 10/01/1984
**Chief Complaint:** Chronic lower back pain with radiation down the left leg.

**History of Present Illness:** Chronic lower back pain exacerbated by physical activity and prolonged sitting. Pain radiates down the left leg and is described as sharp, shooting, occasionally with numbness and tingling. Previous treatments include medications (Acetaminophen, Ibuprofen), topical lidocaine patches, and physical therapy.
**Assessment:** Chronic lower back pain with radiation consistent with sciatica. Degenerative disc disease contributing to symptoms.
**Plan:** Continue current pain management regimen. Referral for physical therapy. Follow-up in 6 weeks.
**Physician:** Marcus David, MD
Procedure: Steroid Injection (Dexamethasone)
**Patient:** Artie Jointston, DOB: 10/01/1984
**Indication:** Chronic lower back pain and sciatica.
**Procedure Details:** Steroid injection administered in the lumbar region for symptomatic relief of pain. Patient tolerated the procedure well and was advised on post-procedure care.
**Follow-up:** Monitor pain relief, follow up in 6 weeks.
**Physician:** Example Physician
**Patient:** Artie Jointston, DOB: 10/01/1984
**Chief Complaint:** Worsening lower back pain and sciatica.

**History of Present Illness:** Chronic back pain, degenerative disc disease, and sciatica. Pain radiating down the left leg, exacerbated by physical activity. Recent medications include Percocet, Lidocaine Patch, and a steroid injection in July 2022.
**Physical Exam:** Tenderness over lumbar spine, decreased ROM, positive straight leg raise on the left.
**Assessment:** Chronic back pain, degenerative disc disease, sciatica, cervicalgia.
**Plan:** Continue current medications, consider another steroid injection, refer to physical therapy. Follow-up in 4 weeks.
**Physician:** Nathanial Blackwell, MD
**Patient:** Artie Jointston, DOB: 10/01/1984
**Chief Complaint:** Persistent lower back pain with radiating pain down the left leg.
**History of Present Illness:** Chronic lower back pain, exacerbated over the past few months.
**Physical Exam:** Forward flexed posture, antalgic gait, decreased ROM in the lumbar spine.
**Assessment:** Chronic lower back pain, decreased lumbar ROM, radicular symptoms.
**Plan:** Initiate core strengthening and lumbar mobility exercises, soft tissue mobilization, apply heat and ice therapy. Follow-up in 4 weeks.
**Physical Therapist:** Jesse McConnel
Procedure: Steroid Injection (Dexamethasone)
**Patient:** Artie Jointston, DOB: 10/01/1984
**Indication:** Chronic lower back pain and sciatica.
**Procedure Details:** Steroid injection administered in the lumbar region for pain relief. Patient tolerated the procedure well and was advised on post-procedure care.
**Follow-up:** Monitor relief, follow-up in 6 weeks.
